===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|ones||lang=enm}} (genitive of {{term|on||lang=enm|one}} used adverbally), from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|ānes||of one}}, genitive of {{m|ang|ān||one}}. Compare {{etyl|osx|-}} {{term|ēnes||once|tr={{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|eens|lang=nl}}|lang=osx}}, {{etyl|goh|-}} {{m|goh|einēst||once}} ({{etyl|de|-}} {{term|einst|lang=de}}). More at {{l|en|one}}, [[-s#Etymology_3|-s]].

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|wŭn(t)s}}, {{IPA|/wʌn(t)s/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-once.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{rhymes|ʌns|lang=en}}
* ''[[one#English|one]]'' and ''[[once#English|once]]'' are pronounced differently from the related words ''[[alone#English|alone]]'', ''[[only#English|only]]'' and ''[[atone#English|atone]]''. Stressed vowels often become [[diphthong]]s over time (Latin ''[[bonus#Latin|b'''o'''na]]'' → Italian ''[[buono|b'''uo'''na]]'' and  Spanish ''[[bueno|b'''ue'''na]]''), and this happened in the [[w:en:Middle Ages|late Middle Ages]] to the words ''[[one#English|one]]'' and ''[[once#English|once]]'', first recorded [[circa|ca]] 1400: the vowel underwent some changes, from ōn → ōōōn → wōn → wōōn → wŏŏn → wŭn.

